naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment willprovide additional fundingfor the development and construction of a hospital facility in the city of Cumberland, WI. The existing facility and equipment have become antiquated and do not adequately address the areas current medical needs. The new facility will enhance access to and delivery of healthcare for an expanded regional area, providing crucial local healthcare options for patients that would otherwise travel over 100 miles for needed care. Plans include increased support for outpatient services as well as new and improved spaces for orthopedists, podiatrists, oncologists, ear, nose and throat specialists, family practice, OB/GYN, cardiologists and expansion of the outpatient and day surgery functionality.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by the Village of Turtle Lake to upgrade their Wastewater Treatment Plant (WWTP) and sewer system.Funds will be used for collection system improvements, new west lift station, headworks and screening in plant, oxidation ditch improvements, membrane technology for waste treatment system, digester improvements, sludge handling improvements, as well as electrical and scada (controls). The original plant was constructed in 2004,has not had any improvements and is in good condition, however thereare now phosphorus effluent and chloride limits.The plant is also experiencing higher flowrates and loadings from industries connected to the wastewater treatment system and these private industries anticipate substantially higher flowrates and nutrient loadings over the next 20 years. The existing WWTP will not be able to meet the nutrient removal requirements without additional upgrades and treatment.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will primarily be used for upgrades to the City of Cheteks wastewater treatment plant (WWTP). The existing WWTP was installed in the 1950s and had upgrades in 1982.The WWTP has several code violations including having residential and commercial structures within 500 feet of the siteand the plantcannot meet the future Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources phosphorus limits, which go in effect in the spring of 2025.The WWTP has reached the end of its useful life and the project will include the construction of a newplant at a new location that is designed to meet future discharge limits. he project also includes upgrades to the existing collection system, construction of a new lift station and new force main.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the water system and wells. Well #1 (constructed in 1933 and reconstructed in 1984) and Well #3 (constructed in 1982) are both subject to a growth of natural biofilm with acid producing bacteria. This change in the water chemistry increases the solubility of manganese and thus the manganese levels of the well water poses a very dangerous risk to the village residents and leaves the water undrinkable. The upgrade and rehabilitation will help reduce corrosion of the pump and well casing in each well and corrosion of lead pipe and copper plumbing in the water distribution system, thus being able to control acceptable manganese levels in drinking water to the residents. The Village will also be receiving funding from the WI Department of Natural Resources for additional sewer and water improvements.

funding_code: GUAR BIOREFINERY ASST PROGRAM-VARIABLE RATE
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a community anaerobic digester in Brown County, Wisconsin. The facility will convert 925,900 gallons per day (gpd) of manure feedstock from 12 local dairies into 1,625 million British Thermal Units (mmBTUs) per day of renewable natural gas (RNG). Feedstock will be pumped to the facility via pipeline from two farms and trucked to the facility from the remaining ten.Two biproducts of this process will be potable water and fiber that will be returned to the farms that provide the feedstock for use as animal bedding. BC Organics process consists of three key technologies: anaerobic digestion, biogas upgrading and cleanup, and nutrient recovery and water reclamation.

project_name: FY19 Sewer - WWTP new, collection upgrade, CTHA extension
funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will provide additional financingfor the wastewater treatment plant (WWTP)funded in 2019. The existing WWTP, dating back to the 1960s, has a rotating biological contractor process that will not be able to meet future phosphorus effluent limits. Due to the deteriorating infrastructure, the plant cannot continue to function without a major upgrade. The current site is close to residential buildings, located in a 100-year flood plain and surrounded by wetlands preventing possible expansion. The citys current wastewater collection system is also in need of repairs and upgrades and experiences high amounts of inflow and infiltration during storms. This project will construct a new WWTPin a new location not located in flood plain or wetlands. The project includes: oxidization ditch technology with fine screen and grit removal, controls linked to SCADA, energy savings initiatives, UV disinfection, septage treatment for phosphorus removal, new outflow location and construction of a new lift station and force main to convey wastewater to the new WWTP location. In conjunction with this project, the city is extending water service to the new industrial park where the WWTP will be located.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make water and wastewater upgrades. The WI Department of Natural Resources notified the city that the water distribution system exceeded lead limits so the city is required to remove all lead service lines and lead-jointed water main pipes. The sanitary sewer mains in the project area are nearing the end of their useful life, have clay tile pipes that are broken and have root intrusions. If left unattended, these issues will cause increased infiltration and inflow at the wastewater treatment plant and increase the risk for customer back-ups. This water and sewer upgrade project will include full reconstruction of approximately five miles of city streets including replacement of about 20,000 feet of lead-jointed water mains and will address failing sanitary sewer collection system components. The removal of all lead components from the water system will reduce the lead levels currently present in the drinking water and return lead levels in the citys drinking water to an acceptable level. The replacement of wastewater collection pipes will remove numerous sags, breaks and intrusions so that the system can operate for many years to come.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund major upgrades to the wastewater treatment facility and system extensions in some portions of the City of Waupun. The improvements to the facility will add a phosphorus removal system by utilizing a new technology that includes advanced treatment with a chemical addition or advanced biological nutrient removal (ABNR). The ABNR system is an algae-based system capable of recovering phosphorus and nitrogen into harvested algae biomass. This addition will assist the city in achieving compliance with its phosphorus limits in the Rock River Basin area.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Lisowe Acres LLC, a dairy farm, purchase and install a 300 kilowatt solar array on their barn roof. funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will provide technical assistance and training to rural microentrepreneurs and microenterprises. The applicant has been providing business assistance to small, rural businesses for over 25 years. Their mission is to create opportunities for people and communities to reduce poverty and increase self-sufficiency. They focus on helping low-income entrepreneurs with start-up business assistance, as well as ongoing assistance. This agency has participated in this program for ten years.

funding_code: (GRANT ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing for the village of Tennyson water system project. The original project included a water tower, improvements to the water utilities well house and water main replacements on two streets. This project is needed due to the new water tower being installed as the water system pressure is about 30 psi higher resulting in numerous water main breaks due to faulty pipes across the system. A majority of the breaks occurred under a state highway right-of-way where the pipe was installed in the 1950s-1960s. The additional funds will be used to replace this section of pipe so it can meet the increased pressure of the system.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment willbe usedto replace aging equipment and allow the wastewater treatment facility (WWTF) meet current and future effluent limits, particularly new stringent phosphoruslimits.The improvements include the following: add new and replace aged site piping, add emergency generator equipment, renovate the administration building and construct a new public works garage, add a waste receiving station, replace influent pumps, construct a new headworks building, construct biological phosphorus removal process tanks, add chemical dosing/mixing facilities, replace aging process equipment in the aeration basins, construct a third final clarifier and upgrade existing clarifiers, upgrade sludge pumping equipment, modify the existing tertiary filters, replace ultraviolet disinfection equipment and digester renovations. In addition to work at the WWTF, the utility intends to replace the main interceptor on Hendricks Street.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade and expand the Village of Wonewoc wastewater treatment facility (WWTF). The WWTF, last updated in 1979, is located in the floodway and has experienced extreme flooding events.The collection system also has significant inflow and infiltration issues and is not able to handle the peak flows during heavy rain events. In 2018, the WWTF exceeded the design flow capacityfive out of 12 months and experienced a treatment facility overflow.Upgrades and expansion include extension of the aeration activated sludge system to a new site and conversion of existing wet well to a new flood-proofed pump station at the existing WWTF to pump the wastewater to the new WWTF in the new location.

naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create infrastructure to expand the sales and use of renewable fuels. Kwik Trip, Inc. is the owner often or more fueling stations. This project will replace65 dispensers and 10 storage tanks at six fueling stations, as well as install 298 dispensers at 25 fueling station, located in Wisconsin, Minnesota, and Iowa. Stations locations impacted by this grant are: Prairie Du Chien, River Falls, Kenosha, Fennimore, Dodgeville, Waukesha, West Bend (3), Crivitz, Medford (2), Beaver Dam, Hayward, Eau Claire, Wisconsin Dells (2), Antigo, and Janesville (2) in Wisconsin; New Ulm, Winona, Cold Spring, and Spring Valley in Minnesota; and Marshalltown, Des Moines, Cedar Rapids (2), Sheldon, Emmetsburg, and Iowa City in Iowa. This project projects to increase the amount of ethanol sold by 45.217,587 gallons per year. The purpose of this funding program is to assist owners of transportation fueling and fuel distribution facilities in activities designed to expand the sales and use of ethanol and biodiesel.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development funding will be used to repair and replace aging infrastructure in the wastewater plant and to increase the capacity of the existing facility to meet future growth needs. The original wastewater treatment facility was constructed in 1979 and has had numerous modifications and upgrades in response to changing flows, loadings, permit requirements and the aging of facilities and equipment. funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve the Edgar Wastewater Treatment Facility (WWTF). The existing WWTF, originally constructed in the 1930s and upgraded in 1968, needs improvements to keep the system running efficiently and within requirements. This project includes improvements that will recondition several of the treatment processes, replace a major portion of the electrical system and will include the conversion of the blower/generator room to a lab/office. These improvements will allow the WWTF to remove phosphorus both chemically and biologically to be able to achieve the phosphorus waste load allocation imposed by the Wisconsin River TMDL (total maximum daily load).

funding_code: CF GRANTS

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase atruck and equipment for the public works department. The new truck will be usedfor the entire township including snow plowing streets and alleys in the downtown section of the town, as well as on pothole patching and hauling an equipment trailer which carries the culvert-thawing equipment in late winter and early spring.The town s existing one-ton truck has 160,000 miles, is at the end of its useful life and experiences many repairs. project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment willbe used by the town of Beaver to renovate the town hall and purchase equipment for thepublic works department. The town hallproject will include the purchase and installation of a generator, renovate both bathrooms to make them ADA compliant and renovate the front doorsincluding installation of power units to make the doors handicap accessible. Electrical updates will also take place on the doors and bathrooms as needed.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the Village of Wilton wastewater treatment facility (WWTF). This project includes upgrading the WWTF to address equipment, lagoon and process deficiencies to meet current and future permit requirements. The existing WWTF system was constructed in 1980 and has historically struggled to meet current discharge limits. The existing lagoons have a number of items needing to be brought into compliance with WI Department of Natural Resource requirements. Most processes and equipment are original to the plant construction and are reaching the end of their useful life and need replacement or upgrading.

This project includes thepurchase of a used 2005garbage truck that has been well maintained and has features that the old truck does not have such as a lifter in the back of the truck to squeeze and lift garbage cans for emptying and can be used for both garbage and recycling. funding_code: HIGHER BLENDS INFRASTRUCTURE INCENTIVE PROGRAM GRANTS - MANDATORY
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create infrastructure to expand the sales and use of renewable fuels. Bulk Petroleum Corporation is the owner of 10 or more fueling stations. This project will replace165 dispensers and 30 storage tanks at 36 fueling stations located inWisconsin, Michigan,Indiana, and Iowa. Stations and locations impacted by this grant are: Salem, Stevens Point, Lodi, Pewaukee, Cudahy, South Milwaukee, Two Rivers, Random Lake, Sturgeon Bay (2), Green Bay, Brussels, Sheyboygan, Waukesha, Milwaukee (2),and Oak Creek in Wisconsin; Grand Rapids (4), Albion, Lansing (3), Kentwood (2) in Michigan; Nineveh, Bedford, North Vernon, Indianapolis, Anderson, Sellersburg, and Scottsburg in Indiana; and Davenport (2) in Iowa. This project projects to increase the amount of ethanol sold by 12,430,314 gallons per year. The purpose of this funding program is to assist owners of transportation fueling and fuel distribution facilities in activities designed to expand the sales and use of ethanol and biodiesel.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding for the village of Clear Lake wastewater treatment plant (WWTP) upgrade. The facility is in need of a major renovation to address aging infrastructure and more stringent discharge permit requirements imposed by the Department of Natural Resources (DNR). The project includes updating facilities to meet the demands of local and industrial users as well as meeting new DNR phosphorus permit requirements. Project improvements include updating treatment processes, new treatment tanks, a new treatment building and improvements/upgrades throughout the facility.

naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)

program: Rural Economic Development Loan and Grant (REDLG)
funding_code: RURAL ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT LOANS (ELECTRIC)
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will finance working capital for a nonprofit organization, Iola Old Car Show, Inc. This annual show dates back to 1972. Each year the show brings over 100,000 attendees to the rural community of Iola, Wis. More than 2,000 volunteers serve nearly 25,000 volunteer hours for the event, and 130 civic organizations garner between $200,000-$300,000 annually as a result of the event. With COVID-19, the show was canceled for 2020, but plans move forward for an in-person or virtual 2021 show. This working capital will allow the organization to maintain operations, saving ten jobs.

funding_code: DISCRETION ASSIST MICROPENTERPRENUERS
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will provide technical assistance and training to rural microentrepreneurs and microenterprises. The applicant is a private non-profit corporation whose mission isto mobilize resources needed to bring about a permanent increase in the ability of low-income people to become economically and emotionally self-sufficient.This agency has participated in this program for ten years.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to aid in the relocation of streets and utilities in a portion of the community thatis located in a flood plain.This project would include roadway infrastructure that serves the community in order to relocate residential and commercial development out of the flood plain, due to repetitive flooding, into the proposed resettlement site.This project is being done in conjunction with sewer and water relocation projects in the same area.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund additional work on the relocation of streets and utilities in a portion of the community that are located in a flood plain. This project would include roadway infrastructure that serves the community in order to relocate residential and commercial development out of the flood plain, due to repetitive flooding, into the proposed resettlement sites. This additional funding will extend the projectto a new street in the resettlement area.This project is being done in conjunction with sewer and water relocation projects in the same area.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to relocate infrastructure in a portion of the community that is located in a floodplain. The Kickapoo River flooded the village six times between 2007 and 2019 which resulted in water pumps failing and sewer mains creating backups in residences and businesses located in the floodplain. After this project is completed, the village will no longer service areas in the designated floodplain area. The funding will include new water distribution lines to provide clean, safe and reliable water in the resettlement areas, including a new well. The sewer improvements will prevent sewer backups related to flooding incidents and allow for the relocating of residential and commercial development out of the floodplain into proposed resettlement sites.

naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by the fire department for the construction of a fire hall to store equipment and conduct fire suppression training and operations.The fire department serves the Town of Couderay and the Town of Hunter,provides mutual aid to Sawyer County and adjacent counties and works with the Department of Natural Resources in fire suppression when assistance is needed.The proposed facility will be a 50x56 pole shed with three bays and a water supply for filling trucks and will also be used as heated storage for firefighting equipment.

funding_code: NATIVE AMERICAN TRIBES COMMUNITY FACILITY GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide financial assistance for improvements to the Lac Courte Oreillies (LCO) Ojibwe College campus buildings. Improvements will be made to the Sustainable Agriculture Research Station (LSARS) including equipment to properly operate the activities it provides to the community and for general upkeep of the grounds and maintaining the crops it produces.In addition, two buildings are in need of upgrades to the HVAC systems so that classes and activities may be performed during the winter months.The College also proposes to address the immediate needs of the LSARS including equipment purchases and roof replacement.This is the seventh year that this recipient has participated in this program.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a wastewater treatment plant (WWTP) for the village of Baldwin, just north of the site. The WWTP is over 30-years old and needs significant upgrades due to biological overloading and larger flows than the design allows for. Additionally, much of the equipment is reaching the end of its useful life and the plant also needs to treat phosphorus. This project is being driven by the WI Department of Natural Resources Pollutant Discharge Elimination Permit and phosphorus upgrades must be completed by fall 2023.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a 32-bed assisted living facility, Vernon Manor, in rural Viroqua, Wis. The facility will be adjacent to a skilled nursing home, therefore providing living facilities and access to medical services for the new residents. This $6.5 million project has secured matching funds from Vernon County, Vernon Electric Cooperative, and Community Development Block Grant. The project will create 15 new jobs.

program: Rural Energy for America Program Renewable Energy Systems and Energy Efficiency Improvement Loans and Grants
funding_code: MAND. RENEW ENERFY SYSTEMS GRANTS UNDER $20,000
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Nordik Meats Incorporated purchase and install a 120 kilowatts (kW) solar system. The system is estimated to generate 167,280 kilowatt hours (kWh) per year, which is enough electricity to power 15 homes.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for working capital to process beef and pork into packaged products by a farmer cooperative. Funds will be used for packaging inventory, processing fees, marketing and distribution.The project will increase theircustomer base by 2,572 customers, increase revenue by $1,100,000 and will create one job.

funding_code: LOCAL AGRICULTURE MARKET RESOURCE PROGRAM (LAMP) VALUE-ADDED PRODUCER GRANTS - COVID
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used for working capital to process milk and cream into sour cream which will be sold in pouches by a farm cooperative.Funds will also be used for marketing.This project will increase their customer base by 30 customers and increase revenue by $1,442,824.Four jobs will be created by this project.

borrower_name: VIROQUA WI, RDA OF THE CITY OF
funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct acity halland safe room thatwill serve the basic needs of the city government and provide additional amenities to meet community needs.The city hall will include administrative offices for staff, public meeting space for common council andother city needs andsmall and large group meeting space to serve city and community functions. It will also serveas the election location, municipal court proceedingsand community safe room.This new building will replace the city hall that is outdated, out of compliance, too small and no longer meets the needs of the City of Viroqua.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will beused to construct a new street to serve a new development area located in the village of Ontario. The village has experienced reoccurring flooding which has caused significant damage to the infrastructure and business community and creates a serious health & safety hazard. The village plans to implement a flood relocation project to avoid the negative impact caused by future floods.The proposed project consists of creating new building sites on high ground that will be resilient to natural disasters and provide necessary infrastructure to support a sustainable community. The new development areas will provide sites for businesses, multi- family residential and single-family residential development.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a new tractor loader with accessories.The villages 2003 backhoe has limited capabilities due to its size and has become a high maintenance vehicle due to extensive use. This project includes the purchase of a new compact truck loader with snow blower and brush cat attachments. This piece of equipment will be used to remove sand/silt and debris after flood events and storms. The brush hog will aid in controlling brush growth along the Kickapoo River and the snow blower attachment will be used to blow snow directly from the street on to trucks. This new equipment will increase efficiency and reduce costs for the Village while providing needed services for the residents.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding for the city of Eagle River wastewater treatment facility (WWTF) upgrade. This project will install disinfection systems at the WWTF and cover the cost and feasibility of leachate pretreatment/treatment at the WWTF along with the nearby landfill. Also included in this project is replacement of equipment that will positively impact efforts to optimize biological phosphorus removal. The WWTF has been receiving landfill leachate and it has experienced difficulty meeting permit limits and receiving the increased volumes of leachate.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional funding for road improvements in the village of Mason. The initial project was obligaed in fiscal year 2020. Funds will be used to rehabilitate the asphalt pavement for roadways without sewer beneath them. Due to aging and lack of adequate base course, the pavement structures are experiencing extensive settlement and deterioration, and will continue to deteriorate if not rehabilitated. Rehabilitation consists of pulverizing and overlaying the roadways, shaping the roadway, paving the roadway, and constructing the shoulder. In addition, four roads have deteriorated beyond rehabilitation and will be reconstructed. Reconstruction includes full excavation of the roadway to construct a new road base, as well as pavement construction and shoulders.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased construction costs and supply chain issues on the following project funded in FY20: Upgrades to the Village of Mason wastewater treatment facility (WWTF). The WWTF system has issues with excess I&I (inflow/infiltration) due in large part to the excess rainfall, and the system not being big enough to handle the flow. The operation of the spray irrigation system has had to be modified from the original design to address greater than average discharge volumes, causing the system to be overloaded which has resulted in surface runoff from the discharge field and violation of the villages WPDES discharge permit. The system will be upgraded to correct deficiencies including: reduction in hydraulic loading to provide the required resting periods and provide control of surface run off; the pump, which is nearing the end of its useful life, will be rebuilt to ensure continued performance; a new transfer pump will be installed to transfer treated wastewater to the proposed irrigation system, and a cold storage building will be constructed to house irrigation equipment during winter as well as vehicles and other equipment for maintaining the sewer utility.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by the city of Thorp to make upgrades to the waste water treatment plant (WWTP). The plant is over 35 years old and in need of upgrades due to growth in the community along with not being able to accept more wastewater without biological overloading and larger flows than the original design. The WWTP has been meeting effluent limits but has been turning away interested industries due to lack of capacity. The lagoons and the holding pond need to be dredged, they have synthetic liners that are ripped and require replacement, and there is also a need for new aeration equipment. This project will include upgrades to the aeration and lining of the lagoons and pond, a new main WWTP, and a new main lift station facility.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a fire ladder truck for the city of Portage. The current Tower 1 is 30 years old, five years past its expected useful life and is beginning to fail. During the annual testing of the apparatus, the testing caused the seals to the large lifting rams to fail resulting in a major repair. These types of failures will only increase with age, placing the fire fighters in greater danger in fire and rescue operations. The city of Portage supports many of the small towns and villages in the area with fire call services. Some of these small towns do have some industrial based businesses where the ladder truck will provide a safer working environment for the fire fighters. The city of Portage also has a historic downtown area with some buildings four or more stories high, where the ladder truck will be a great asset to helping protect the surrounding areas. Funds will be used to purchase a new ladder truck to serve the city of Portage and the surrounding area and will allow the city to move the existing truck to a reserve status providing a back-up to respond to calls if needed.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a facility for a community based non-profit preschool and childcare center located in Mount Horeb. The Childrens Community School (CCS) was founded in 1976, and currently has 60 children enrolled in programs designed for children 18 months to six years old. The school has been steadily expanding programs as the community grows and families change and are nearing full capacity. Issues at the current facility need to be addressed include: lack of classroom space, lack of adequate bathrooms, limited storage, American Disability Act compliance, lack of kitchen space, security issues, and age and condition of the building. Funds will be used to construct a new facility so CCS can expand their programs and enrollment, and better serve the growing needs of the community.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the waste water treatment facility. The system consists of three stabilization lagoons, a dosing chamber, a recirculating sand filter and flow monitoring/sampling equipment. The waste water treatment facility discharges treated waste water to a receiving stream during the warm weather months when the recirculating and sand filters are in operation. The sand filters are open to the elements and cannot operate during freezing weather conditions. This investment will build a cover over the final lagoon to minimize the effects of freezing temperatures, chemical addition to the lagoons with a pumping system and lagoon mixer addition for phosphorus treatment and compliance with WI DNR limitation. The reduction of phosphorus will also improve the conditions of the Rock River which the Lebanon SD discharges into.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a satellite healthcare facility in Fennimore, Wisconsin. The facility will be located 12 miles from the main campus to better serve the local area population decreasing travel times for residents in remote areas. The clinic will provide patients with high-quality healthcare including primary services as well rehabilitation, X-ray, and lab processing. The facility will also allow employers in that community to retain their workforce, including the ability for workers to get their healthcare needs in town rather than driving out of town, potentially missing work time or relocating out of the community.

The new system is expected to save $3,195 a year and replace 27,080 kilowatt hours (kWh) (107 percent of the business energy use) per year.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the sewer collection and lift station system in the Village of Lyndon Station. The goal of this project is to address the phosphorus mandate being imposed on the village by the WI Dept. of Natural Resources. Upgrades are planned to be made to the ditch to incorporate bio and chemical removal of phosphorus and a proposed reed bed sludge treatment/disposal system. All of the major components of the current system were constructed in 2000, when the lagoon system was replaced with the mechanical treatment system, with the exception of the fine screen. This project also includes general improvements to the existing facilities and improvements to the collection/lift station systems.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a 75,000 square foot critical access hospital facility in the city of Darlington, Wisconsin. The existing hospital was constructed in the early 1950s and is now outdated, landlocked, and unable to meet modern healthcare delivery standards. There are no opportunities to renovate or expand on the existing site. The disjointed departmental zoning and patient flow add to the deficiencies of the hospital, with the current layout creating a confusing, inefficient patient experience. The new facility will be located on a 36-acre parcel and designed to meet the current and future needs of the hospital. Once completed the new facility will feature a hospital with 24 beds, an emergency department, lab, radiology department, surgical facilities, dietary facility, rehabilitation space, eyecare clinic, and administration offices.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the sanitary sewer system in the Village of Blanchardville. The waste water treatment facility was originally constructed in 1952; significantly upgraded in 1971; and upgraded once more in 1990. The facility requires a comprehensive upgrade to extend the life of the plant for 20 years and to meet current and future effluent limits. In a proposed sewer replacement area, the clay tile sewer lines have excessive root intrusions that have required jetting to prevent blockage of the lines. This project will consist of several upgrades including sitework/paving and piping improvements, replacement of influent pumps, renovations to buildings, rebuilding/replacing oxidation ditch and clarifier equipment, installing new UV disinfection, and the addition of chemical feed facilities for phosphorus treatment. Sewer lines will be replaced with new PVC pipe, along with required roadway reconstruction and replacement of other utilities. This project will be done in conjunction with water distribution system upgrades in the same area, and will provide a sustainable, long-term solution for the Villages infrastructure needs.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the water distribution system in the Village of Blanchardville. The water system is composed of 4-inch to 12-inch diameter cast iron pipe that is 50-60 years old. The water mains in the project area are 4-inch and 6-inch, with N. Main Street having a 4-inch diameter water main that does not meet Wisconsin Code to provide water for fire protection and to serve fire hydrants. For the proposed water main replacement area, there have been numerous breaks particularly on Baker Street. The Village has limited options for stopping flow to the areas with breaks when they occur as there are limited valves along the project area streets. This project will include replacing aging water mains on Mound, Baker and N. Main streets with 8-inch diameter ductile iron or PVC pipes. This project will be done in conjunction with sewer system upgrades in the same area, and will provide a sustainable, long-term solution for the Villages infrastructure needs.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a generator to run the wastewater treatment plant (WWTP) in the village of Coleman. The generator currently being used is 40 years old, unreliable, and only 40 kilowatts (kW). If the village of Coleman were to experience an outage for more than 24 hours the WWTP would not be able to operate, creating an emergency. The new unit will be 250 kW and connect to a new 400-amp transfer switch. In case of a power outage, the WWTP will be able to continue to function due to this upgrade and will allow the village to meet new limit requirements set forth by the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources.

funding_code: CF GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a law enforcement vehicle and equipment for the village of Crivitz. The current vehicle is a 2007 Chevrolet Tahoe and needs to be replaced as it needs repairs and parts that are no longer available. The current equipment is six to eight years old and has been repaired as much as possible but has reached the end of its serviceable life. Replacement of the equipment is necessary so it can interface as needed with other law enforcement systems in the county and state. The vehicle and related equipment will help the department continue to perform their duties as law enforcement officers effectively and timely.

Improvements to Glenn Miller Hall include a structural inspection and any repairs needed for safety and aesthetics, and installation of new flooring to also address safety concerns. funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make water system infrastructure improvements in the E. Washington Street area. The water mains were installed in 1936, and the city has had to replace hydrants and valves within the project area due to deterioration and seeping. This project will replace all existing water main and valves, hydrants, and services to properties. These improvements will reduce maintenance costs related to water main breaks, seeping valves, and leaking hydrants, and provide additional distribution capacity for fire flows in the area. This water project will be done in conjunction with sewer system upgrades in the same area.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make water system infrastructure improvements in the State Hwy 22 area. Improvements include new water mains, hydrants, and valves. The new, wider water mains will provide better flow for emergency fire rescue and prevent continued monetary loss of repairs for seeping valves or leaking hydrants. This water project will be done in conjunction with sewer upgrades in the same area.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make sewer system infrastructure improvements in the E. Washington Street area. The sanitary sewer mains are made of clay pipe and very brittle with cracks, mineral deposits, and root penetration in a large percentage of pipelines. There have been numerous sanitary sewer breaks over the last two decades, resulting in significant increases in the inflow and infiltration. This project will replace sanitary sewer, manholes, and connections made to cross street sewer mains. These improvements will eliminate maintenance costs, improve health and safety by reducing potential for flooding, and provide additional capacity to reduce inflow and infiltration. This sewer project will be done in conjunction with water system upgrades in the same area.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund street reconstruction and utility improvements in the Oneida Avenue area of city of Rhinelander. The citys water mains, sanitary sewers, and storm sewers in the Oneida Avenue Street project area are 30 to 60 years old and need replacement. A portion of the water main is less than 6" in diameter and does not meet current code requirements for fire protection. The city has recorded numerous events of sewer backups/plugging in the project area and has issued trickle water notices for 23 locations to prevent freezing. This project will include utility and street improvements within the city on Oneida Avenue, E. King St., S. Anderson St., and Conro St. Water distribution lines will be replaced concurrently with the water portion of the project in partnership with the Wisconsin DNR Safe Drinking Water Loan Program.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a new Waste Water Treatment Facility (WWTF) in the Village of Prentice. Recent evaluations and planning documents for the facility identified numerous equipment, structural, process, control, and electrical deficiencies. The facility was constructed in 1978 and underwent minor upgrades in 1997 and 2008, which included the addition of a sludge storage tank and fine screening. Influent pumps installed in 2012 are the most recent equipment replacement. The equipment and structures have been well maintained, but most are over 40 years old now, well beyond the normal useful equipment life of 15 to 25 years. Due to the extent of the deficiencies and the facilitys age, estimated costs, and operational costs, the village plans to construct a new WWTF at a different location on the same site. The process will be the same activated sludge package plant process as the previous which minimizes costs, operator training, and footprint, while still meeting the Villages needs.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct an addition and make renovations to the existing library. The city of Baraboos existing library lacks adequate space to serve the residents of the city and the surrounding townships, due to a fifty percent increase in population served and usage. The library was built in 1903 and remodeled several times in the past. It no longer meets current codes, is expensive to maintain and lacks the quality technology and space to meet the service needs of the community. The building is a landmark in Baraboo, located in the historic downtown just a block off the "Square" (or the heart of downtown Baraboo) and too valuable to vacate, therefore, many hours and great minds have worked on this project to preserve the historic facility but make the necessary expansions and additions to meet the growing needs of the community and staff of the library. The librarys goal for the new facility is to meet the needs of the community to enhance the learning, connection, and growth opportunities for all residents of the Baraboo area.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a Waste Water Treatment Facility (WWTF), force main and major lift station. The original WWTF was constructed in 1939 and has undergone upgrades between 1969 to 2016. The facility is currently overloaded based on average flows and loads, and severely overloaded during periods of peak loads and high flows. Additional capacity is needed to meet the citys needs for the next 20 years and to comply with phosphorus water quality limits the existing facility does not meet. In addition, some processes and equipment are reaching the end of their useful life and need replacement or upgrading. The location of the existing WWTF is within the floodway of the Baraboo River and experienced historic flooding in 2008 and 2018. Funds will be for the construction of a new WWTF out of the floodway at a city-owned site and will allow for future growth of the city and comply with phosphorus water quality limits.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make upgrades to sewer system infrastructure. The village has observed significant inflow and infiltration at its municipal waste water treatment plant during rainfall events. Televising of the clay sanitary sewer mains indicate leaky and displaced joints, protruding lateral taps, root penetration, and deterioration. This project will help construct a new gravity sewer system and replace sewer mains and laterals made of plastic. These improvements are more watertight and will accommodate future growth. This project is being done in conjunction with water infrastructure improvements being made in the same areas of the village.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to make upgrades to the villages water system infrastructure. The village has experienced several water main breaks along Main Street and mineral build up in water main piping along Cedar Avenue. The breaks result in unnecessary water loss and expensive repairs, and the mineral build up can reduce available water flow during a fire or other public safety emergency. Funds for this project will be used for the reconstruction of water mains in the affected areas with to solve the existing issues and accommodate future growth in the village. This project is being done in conjunction with sewer upgrades in the same areas of the village.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by the village of Glenbeulah to upgrade the water supply system. The public water supply system within the proposed project area is inadequate for continued operation without reconstruction. The water main is cast iron, which has experienced two breaks in recent years. Additionally, the water main along Barrett Street is undersized and does not meet the capacity for future zoned residential development on adjacent agricultural parcels. This investment will help to build new watermains, hydrant relocations, curb stops and connection, and HDPE water service. This water project is being done in conjunction with sewer system upgrades in the same areas of the village.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the villages sanitary sewer collection system. The system within the proposed project area is inadequate for continued use without reconstruction. The clay pipe sanitary sewer installed in the 1950s is in poor condition resulting in significant infiltration and inflow loading to the system and televising of the system indicating tree root intrusion. This project will include replacing deteriorating clay sewer pipe with PVC sanitary sewer pipes, new sanitary manholes, sanitary laterals, and sanitary lateral connections in the project area. This sewer project is being done in conjunction with water main replacements in the same areas of the village.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the water system in the Village of Eleva. The system is not functioning as the village needs, and the water supply currently exceeds the allowable levels of iron and manganese due a deficient sand filter. The water treatment plant is more than 70 years old, outdated, and has surpassed its useful life. Well #1 is providing sufficient water to the system currently, but the village has had to reduce the flow rate through the filter, reducing the fill rate of the water tower and is not ideal for the long term. Because Well #1 is the only source of water in the community, there is a risk of well failure that would result in no water supply to the community. This project will include a new water treatment plant and water main connecting Well #2 and the new water treatment plant, updates to the Well #1 well house, and a centralization of the office and equipment storage into one location for the water treatment plant.

The system is not functioning as the village needs, and the water supply currently exceeds the allowable levels of iron and manganese due a deficient sand filter. The water treatment plant is more than 70 years old, outdated, and has surpassed its useful life. Well #1 is providing sufficient water to the system currently, but the village has had to reduce the flow rate through the filter, reducing the fill rate of the water tower and is not ideal for the long term. Because Well #1 is the only source of water in the community, there is a risk of well failure that would result in no water supply to the community. This project will include a new water treatment plant and water main connecting Well #2 and the new water treatment plant, updates to the Well #1 well house, and a centralization of the office and equipment storage into one location for the water treatment plant.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a law enforcement vehicle and equipment for the village of Redgranite Police Department. The village is hiring a new officer to serve the residents of the village, the population of the Redgranite Correctional Institute and surrounding areas within Waushara County. The only vehicle available for the new officer to use as a patrol unit is over 11 years old, has outdated equipment and in need of replacement. Along with having several costly repairs, it is unreliable, rusting through the sheet metal and much of the specialized police equipment within and attached to the vehicle is reaching the end of its useful service life. Funds will be used to purchase a new vehicle with new radar equipment, security cameras and monitor, and a surveillance trailer with camera.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY21: This Rural Development investment will be used by the Village of Turtle Lake to upgrade their Wastewater Treatment Plant (WWTP) and sewer system. Funds will be used for collection system improvements, new west lift station, headworks and screening in plant, oxidation ditch improvements, membrane technology for waste treatment system, digester improvements, sludge handling improvements, as well as electrical and scada (controls). The original plant constructed in 2004 has not had any improvements and is in good condition, however, there is now a phosphorus effluent limit and current chloride limit. The plant is also experiencing higher flowrates and loadings from industries connected to the wastewater treatment system, and these private industries anticipate substantially higher flowrates and nutrient loadings over the next 20 years and the existing WWTP will not be able to meet the nutrient removal requirements without additional upgrades and treatment.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing for upgrades to water and sewer systems of the city of Bloomer, Wisconsin. The Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources notified the city that the water distribution system exceeded lead limits. The city must remove all lead service lines and lead-jointed water main pipes. The sanitary sewer mains in the project area are near the end of their useful life and have root intrusions and broken clay-tile pipes. If left unrepaired, these will cause increased infiltration and inflow at the Wastewater Treatment Plant and increase the risk for customer back-ups. This water and sewer upgrade project will include full reconstruction of approximately five miles of city streets including replacement of about 20,000 feet of lead-jointed water main and will address failing sanitary sewer collection system components. The removal of all lead components from the water system will reduce the lead levels currently present in the drinking water and return levels in the citys drinking water to an acceptable level. The replacement of wastewater collection pipes will remove numerous sags, breaks and intrusions to maintain an operational system for many years.

These issues if left unattended will cause increased I/I at the WWTP and increase the risk for customer back-ups. funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY22: Upgrades to the City of Thorps wastewater treatment plant (WWTP). The plant is more than 35 years old and in need of upgrades due to growth in the community along with not being able to accept more wastewater without biological overloading and larger flows than the original design. The WWTP has been meeting effluent limits but has been turning away interested industries due to lack of capacity. The lagoons and the holding pond need to be dredged, they have synthetic liners that are ripped and require replacement, and there is also a need for new aeration equipment. This project will include upgrades to the aeration and lining of the lagoons and pond, a new main WWTP, and a new main lift station facility.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs and an expanded work scope during the final design process on the following project funded in FY21: Upgrade the Lebanon Sanitary District (S.D.) wastewater treatment facility (WWTF). The existing system consists of three stabilization lagoons, a dosing chamber, a recirculating sand filter and flow monitoring/sampling equipment. The existing WWTF discharges treated wastewater to a receiving stream during the warm weather months when the recirculating and sand filters are in operation. The sand filters are open to the elements and cannot operate during freezing weather conditions. Upgrades will include a cover over the final lagoon to minimize the effects of freezing temperatures, chemical addition to the lagoons with a pumping system and lagoon mixer addition for phosphorus treatment and compliance with WI DNR limitation. The reduction of phosphorus will also improve the conditions of the Rock River which the Lebanon SD discharges into.

borrower_name: STURGEON BAY HISTORICAL SOCIETY FOUNDATION, INC.
funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Arts, Entertainment, and Recreation (71)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to fund the Door County Granary project that is intended to be an interpretive museum to celebrate the rich agrarian heritage of Sturgeon Bay and its surrounding communities. Recognizing the value of its robust wood construction, spacious interior, and important place in the history of the community, the Sturgeon Bay Historical Society Foundation Inc. in collaboration with other stakeholders, reclaimed the building for civic use as a museum. These alternations include new openings for accessible ingress and egress, Mechanical, Electrical, Plumbing, and Fire Protection systems, new openings for daylight and ventilation, internal stairs, an elevator, and minor landscape modifications to provide compliant accessible pathways. A piping system has been installed beneath the foundation to vent methane from the soil, reducing its impact on both the site and the building. This addition also includes prep kitchen space, public restrooms, and a stair tower providing a second means of egress from the proposed granary upper level.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a law enforcement vehicle for the Augusta law enforcement department. The Augusta Department has three patrol vehicles, one being obligated to their K9 handler, and another to the school resource officer. The third patrol vehicle is left for general patrol and law enforcement services, which results in an inability to properly respond to all calls. Additionally, if the primary vehicle becomes mechanically disabled it would leave the area vulnerable to no law enforcement response. This project will benefit the residents of Augusta and the surrounding area including the town of Bridge Creek by ensuring the department has ample means to respond and serve the community quickly and efficiently.

funding_code: CY 2022  REGULAR GRANTS DIV N
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a replacement multi-purpose truck for the Town of Wyalusing. The towns existing truck from 2006 has had many repairs, a rusting, cracked frame, and is nearing the end of its useful life. This project includes the purchase of a new truck that would be equipped with a stainless-steel box which is more rust resistant, and additional lighting that would provide extra illumination as a key safety feature. This multi-purpose truck is the focal point of maintaining the town roads and keeping the roads open, and is responsible for all snow plowing, rock hauling, filling cold patch, removal of storm damage and winter sanding of roads. main purpose of this truck is responsible for all snow plowing, hauling rock, filling cold patch, removal of storm damage, and winter sanding of roads.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a fire station. The fire department provides service not only to the city of Platteville, but also to all or portions of the townships of Platteville, Smelser, Lima, Harrison and Ellenboro in Grant County, and townships of Elk Grove and Belmont in Lafayette County. The existing station was constructed in 1964 and no longer provides enough space for the fire department and its vehicles and apparatuses. A one-way parking lot that wraps around the building provides limited space to house vehicles and equipment but is not big enough for volunteers to park when arriving for emergency incidents, which negatively affects response times. This project will include the construction of a 31,900 square foot fire station that will be able to meet the departments needs as well as provide ample parking for volunteers and emergency responders. The new building will be Americans with Disabilities Act compliant, meet modern day best-practice standards for separate decontamination and personal protective equipment cleaning/storage zones and the apparatus bays, and will meet International Building Code or National Fire Protection Association standards for air exchange ventilation.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: OFFICES OF PHYSICIANS (EXCEPT MENTAL HEALTH SPECIALISTS)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace the Mineral Point clinic which is housed in a building built in 1880. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic there has been a drastic increase in patient needs for services which cannot be accommodated by the outdated facility. This project will include the construction of a new clinic building which will create an up to date and Americans with Disabilities Act compliant facility. In addition to an updated facility, the clinic will include a drive thru pharmacy to increase the ability to socially distance and will provide additional clinic space for patient access to health care professionals. New equipment at the facility will be up to date and allow the clinic to provide additional and timely medical services to the community as well as provide additional testing for COVID-19 and vaccination distribution.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY21: Upgrade and expand the Village of Wonewocs waste water treatment facility (WWTF). The WWTF, last updated in 1979, is located in the floodway and has experienced extreme flooding events. The collection system also has significant inflow and infiltration issues and in turn, is not able to handle the peak flows during heavy rain events. In 2018, the WWTF exceeded the design flow capacity five out of 12 months and experienced a treatment facility overflow. Upgrades and expansion include extension of the aeration activated sludge system to a new site, and conversion of existing wet well to a new floodproofed pump station at the existing WWTF to pump the waste water to the new WWTF in the new location.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be to construct a new 600,000-gallon water tower, make improvements to an existing water tower and reconstruct 6722 linear feet of water mains in the Village of Bristol, Wisconsin. A combination of well capacity plus storage capacity, is inadequate to meet current fire flow demands to the village. The village must operate at least one well continuously to ensure a sudden demand does not drain the tower, causing the system to lose pressure and lead to a boil water notice. The village has indicated that utility operators have had to sleep at a wellhouse to ensure system pressure is maintained while the existing water tower is down for maintenance. The water system has experienced 150 water main breaks since 2015 when it began tracking them and have identified several areas with a concentration of main breaks in need of repair. An analysis determined there are hydraulic limitations due to distribution system pipe sizes that do not allow for the village to operate all three wells at the same time without overflowing the existing water tower and over pressurizing the distribution system.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a 75,000 square foot replacement critical access hospital facility in the city of Darlington, Wisconsin. The existing hospital was constructed in the early 1950s, with numerous additions following, and is now outdated, landlocked and is unable to meet modem healthcare delivery standards. There are no opportunities to renovate or expand on the existing site. The disjointed departmental zoning and patient flow add to the deficiencies of the hospital, with the current layout creating a confusing, inefficient patient experience. The new facility would be located on a 36-acre parcel in the city of Darlington, Wisconsin and would be designed to meet current and future needs of the hospital. Once completed the new facility will feature a hospital with 24 beds, an emergency department, lab, radiology department, surgical facilities, dietary facility, rehabilitation space, eyecare clinic, and administration offices.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY21: Improvements to the Village of Edgars Waste Water Treatment Facility (WWTF). The existing WWTF, originally constructed in the 1930s, and upgraded in 1968, needs improvements to keep the system running efficiently and within requirements. This project includes improvements that will recondition several of the treatment processes, replace a major portion of the electrical system, and will include the conversion of the blower/generator room to a lab/office. These improvements will allow the WWTF to remove phosphorus both chemically and biologically to achieve the phosphorus waste load allocation imposed by the Wisconsin River total maximum daily load.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY21: Upgrades to the Village of Wilton waste water treatment facility (WWTF). This project includes upgrading the WWTF to address equipment, lagoon, and process deficiencies to meet current and future permit requirements. The existing WWTF system was constructed in 1980 and has historically struggled to meet current discharge limits. The existing lagoons have a number of items needing to be brought into compliance within WDNR requirements. Most processes and equipment are original to the plant construction and are reaching the end of their useful life and need replacement or upgrading.

The skid loader has seen increasing maintenance costs associated with the number of hours on the machine affecting the efficiency of the engine and drive train. funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand and renovate the Lakes Country Public Library in northern Oconto County. The proposed addition will add 3,075 square feet to the existing building built in 1981. The library is currently unable to provide adequate learning and programming opportunities for the local community due to size limitations, lack of current technology, and lack of public school in the area. Funds will be used for new flooring, LED lighting, outlets, siding, automatic doors, Americans with Disabilities Act compliant family restroom, outside materials drop box, storage space, and two additional high-efficiency heating, ventilation, and air conditioning units. Other improvements include enlarging the Childrens Area, creating a Teen Zone; adding two small meeting rooms, one large 30-person community room, soft seating area, circulation desk area, directors office, kitchenette, and storage. The existing and proposed addition will be fully accessible upon completion.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing for sewer system upgrades on East Washington Street in the city of Gillett, Wisconsin. The project will replace the sanitary sewer, manholes, and cross-street sewer-mains connections. These improvements will help eliminate maintenance costs, improve health and safety, reduce flooding potential, and provide additional capacity. This sewer project will be done with water system upgrades in the same area. The project areas sanitary sewer is vitrified clay pipe in poor condition. It is very brittle with cracks, mineral deposits, and root penetration. There have been numerous breaks in the project area over the last two decades resulting in significant increases in inflow and infiltration. This sanitary sewer area needs to be replaced.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing for water system upgrades on East Washington Street in the city of Gillett, Wisconsin. The project will replace all water mains, valves, and hydrants with 8-inch-diameter water mains interconnected to all cross-street distribution mains. These improvements will reduce maintenance and repair costs from water-main breaks, valve seeps, and hydrant leaks. The project will supply additional fire-flow distribution capacity in this area. It will be done along with sewer system upgrades in the same area. Since 1936 the project area has a history of water main breaks. The current cast-iron 6-inch-diameter water main is in poor to very poor condition and susceptible to breaks and water loss.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to perform several upgrades to the water system as well as repainting and recoating the inside of the water tower. This project also includes installing a new watermain from Well 6, thru the park and in E 3rd Street, eliminating dead-end watermain by adding a watermain loop from Chapley Ave to Case Ave, and constructing a sampling line within an existing park shelter off this new main for Well 6. Notable associated items are valves, a hydrant, and both street and turf restoration. Funds will also be used for sewer improvements to enhance biological digestion, modifying aeration and the Variable Frequency Drives (VFDs) as well as mixers. Lastly, improvements are also planned to the monitoring and control systems (SCADA) to improve operation efficiency of the plant. This project is being done in conjunction with sewer upgrades in the same areas of the village.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used by the City of Burlington to purchase a ladder truck for the fire department. The fire departments 1996 ladder truck is approaching the end of its useful life and is frequently out of service for repairs, resulting in the inability to respond to emergency calls for service. Maintenance costs on the aged vehicle also continue to rise causing a strain on the department and city budgets. As the city grows and looks to future development, there are buildings in the city being constructed that are taller than in the past and would require a ladder truck that has a longer reach to effectively respond to structure fires and rescue operations for these larger buildings.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY21: Relocation of infrastructure in a portion of the Village of Viola community that are in a floodplain. The Kickapoo River flooded the Village in 2007, 08, 10, 16, 18 & 19, which resulted in sewer mains in the floodplain no longer servicing a habitable area. This project would include new sewer mains to replace mains in an abandoned area in the floodplain and make the necessary improvements to the system to relocate residential and commercial development out of the floodplain into proposed resettlement sites. This project would be done in conjunction with water main relocation and street replacement in the same areas.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY20: Upgrade and expand the villages water system. The village has benzene contaminants in well # 1, their only water source, and will be using the funds to pay for temporary treatment of water until a suitable well site is found. Funds will also be used for well site investigation, testing, and the construction of new well #2 and well house. The higher-than-normal levels of benzene the village is experiencing is resulting in a health and sanitary issue for the community water system.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY22: This Rural Development investment will be used to upgrade the water system in the Village of Eleva. The existing system is not functioning as the village needs, and the water supply currently exceeds the allowable levels of iron and manganese due a deficient sand filter. The water treatment plant is more than 70 years old, outdated, and has surpassed its useful life. Well #1 is providing sufficient water to the system currently, but the village has had to reduce the flow rate through the filter, reducing the fill rate of the water tower and is not ideal for the long term. Because well #1 is the only source of water in the community, there is a risk of well failure that would result in no water supply to the community. This project will include a new water treatment plant and water main connecting well #2 and the new water treatment plant, updates to the well #1 well house, and a centralization of the office and equipment storage into one location for the water treatment plant.
