funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WASTE DISPOSAL ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide additional financing due to increased project bid costs on the following project funded in FY20: City of Osseo wastewater treatment system. The existing 1961 system that was upgraded in 1985 and 2001, has several unit processes that have either exceeded their useful life, are operating over design capacity, experiencing operational issues, or were not designed to comply with future phosphorus limits. This project includes significant improvements to the system including upgrades to the outdated equipment that has reached its useful life, and improvements to lift stations. The wastewater treatment facility upgrade will also address a number of issues in terms of meeting the Citys WPDES permit requirements which pertain to an overall health and safety issue as it relates to the environment and create a more energy efficient/cost effective and safer facility.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and install a backup generator operated by by the Adams County Fire District (ACFD) for the fire station, located in the Adams, Wisconsin. The ACFD is a volunteer fire department, and the current fire station was built approximately five years ago. At the time of construction, the original plan was to include a backup generator. Due to an increase in construction costs, the generator was not able to be included in the original build. Consequently, the fire station presently does not have a backup generator. Without backup power, the ACFD is vulnerable to power outages. If a power outage were to occur during a very cold period, the firefighting equipment could experience serious damage. The county is at risk of having limited fire coverage in the event of severe storms if the power were to go out.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with construction of a library operated by by the village of Oregon. Increasing from 10,500 to 31,257 square feet, the new library will provide the additional space needed to provide essential library services to the growing community with additional space for critical staff functions and community members alike. borrower_name: BRANDON PUBLIC LIBRARY INC., FRIENDS OF THE
funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Information (51)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to expand the Brandon Public Library, which is located on the lower level of a historic building that was built in 1897 and is not Americans with Disability Act (ADA) compliant. The second floor houses the Brandon Historical Society and has some storage space for the library. The library has been in the same location since it was started in 1913 and outgrew its space long ago. This project will include a single-story addition to the east of the existing library consisting of 1,334 square feet on the first floor. The total first floor of the existing library and addition is 2,794 square feet. Two openings in the wall between the existing library and the addition will be added at the first-floor level and the existing library will be renovated with a conference room and new finishes. The improvements will include lounge seating, reading areas, workspaces, a community meeting room, additional computer workstations, accessible ADA-compliant restrooms, and finally well-designed, brightly lighted, and age-appropriate spaces, all with additional shelf space for more resources.

The indoor furnishings will include furniture for children to sit and work on homework, and kitchen cabinets to assist in serving snacks.

naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: OTHER JUSTICE, PUBLIC ORDER, AND SAFETY ACTIVITIES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to design and construct a new emergency management system (EMS) station. The EMS building located in Laona, Wisconsin failed to pass inspection. The building owners determined building improvements are not financially feasible, which resulted in an eviction from the building. This left 911 ambulance services to area townships and the Forest County Potawatomi reservation including the hotel and casino, unmaintainable. The funds will be used to consolidate two current stations into one new central location to supply 911 services to the townships of Blackwell, Caswell, Carter, Laona, Ross and Wabeno, and the Forest County Potawatomi Reservation. This new facility will be capable of housing six ambulances, will include a classroom training space, walk-in triage room, dayroom kitchen and an operations emergency command center.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
naics_description: OTHER FIRE/RESCUE & PUBLIC SAFETY RELATED SERVICES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to aid the county of Grant with the replacement of the countys failing and inadequate public safety communication system. The current system relies on outdated components/technology and is not able to meet public safety standards. Due to past funding constraints, the system was pieced together over time without proper engineering. This project will fund the planned construction of six new radio towers as well as public safety communications equipment for placement on a total of eleven towers throughout the region. This project will also fund mobile and portable radios. The new radio system will exclusively serve rural communities, and the improvements will solve communications problems that have plagued the rural public safety responders for many decades. The current and future system is used by twenty rural Fire Departments, 13 Ambulance Providers, six Emergency Medical Response Departments and nine Law Enforcement Agencies.

naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an aerial ladder truck for the city of Monroes fire department. The fire departments 1990 ladder truck is approaching the end of useful life and is frequently out of service for repairs, resulting in the inability to respond to emergency calls. Maintenance costs continue to rise causing a strain on the department and city budgets. As the city grows and looks to future development, there are buildings in the city being constructed that are taller than in the past and would require a ladder truck that has a longer reach to effectively respond to structure fires and rescue operations for these larger buildings. A new ladder truck will provide the modern safety features necessary for safe and efficient emergency response.

funding_code: SEC. 5 HIGHER BLENDS INFRASTRUCTURE INCENTIVE PROGRAM GRANT  - IRA
naics_industry_sector: Other or Not Defined
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create infrastructure to expand the sales and use of renewable fuels. Bulk Petroleum Corporation is the owner of more than 10 fueling stations. This project will install 73 E15 dispensers, 7 E85 dispensers, 33 B20 dispensers, 31 ethanol storage tanks, and 22 biodiesel storage tanks at 24 fueling stations located in Wisconsin, Iowa, Michigan, Indiana, and Kentucky. Station locations impacted by this grant are: IA - Davenport (2); IN - Columbus, North Vernon, Nineveh, and Bedford; KY - Louisville; MI - Lansing, and Grand Rapids (3); WI - Green Bay (3), Wisconsin Rapids (2), Black River Falls, Sheboygan Falls, Two Rivers, Sturgeon Bay, Milwaukee (2), Oak Creek, Sheboygan, Luxemburg, and Cudahy. This project projects to increase the amount of biofuels sold by 7,841,796 gallons per year.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist Lac Courte Oreilles Ojibwe University to construct a student housing building and all associated infrastructure. The university does not currently have any on-campus student housing making the university less attractive to potential students and negatively impacting enrollment. Funds will be used for the construction of student housing that will occupy approximately 10 acres at the main campus located on the tribal lands in the city of Hayward. This new two-story building will provide approximately 90 beds, study rooms, school store, self-serve laundry, as well as on-site parking. Housing for students on school grounds will make the campus amenities comparable to other universities in the region, with the goal of increasing student enrollment which will allow for growth of academic offerings and programs that align with the long-term vision of the university.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to remodel and update several structures on Riverwood Nature Center Inc.s 35-acre property, that was built in phases from the early 1900s through the 1980s. The Visitor Center, Youth and Senior Activity Center, Environmental Learning Center and other buildings are in need of various updates such as heating, ventilation, air conditioning, insulation and plumbing, American with Disabilities Act access ramps, windows, and other building code required improvements. By updating the structures Riverwood Nature Center will be able to continue maintaining, preserving, and protecting this interpretive nature center by creating public amenities and community facilities that will allow for education and classrooms, nature trails and accessible restrooms.

funding_code: FY22 CONGRESSIONALLY DIRECTED SPENDING
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a new fire station. The current facility was originally built as a beer warehouse in 1964. The city purchased and remodeled the building in 1994 to replace the communitys only fire station. Most of the renovations were completed by fire fighters using salvaged materials from the local technical college. While the building has been serviceable, deficiencies were recognized as early as 2002. By 2021, it was made clear that the current building is severely inadequate and prohibits necessary growth. The new station will be approximately 26,900 square feet and will serve as the sole base of operations for the Viroqua Fire Department. The new station will help to positively contribute to fire fighter performance, response time, safety equipment storage/maintenance, and the ability to expand services to meet the needs of the greater Viroqua community.
